Package com.ddt.dependencyutils

Class Dependency<K, V>

java.lang.Object
com.ddt.dependencyutils.Dependency<K, V>
Type Parameters:
K - key type
V - value type
public class Dependency<K,V> extends Object
TODO: Implement recursive equals such that the comparison checks whether the comparators have identical dependency trees. TODO: Implement an iterator which recurses the tree according to serializing scheme (roots down or leaves up).

Dependency (and Dependency tree). This class represents both a node in a Dependency tree and the multi-rooted tree itself. Adding and removing nodes in the tree are supported via addDependency and removeDependency.

While Dependency supports multiple roots e.g. Y depends on X and X depends on A,B and C while A,B and C have no dependencies and so are root nodes, it does not naturally guarantee awareness of its full context. For example, if Z depends on Y and Y depends on A, B, C and D, it would be possible to derive a list of all the root nodes (A,B,C and D) and therefore have access to their respective Dependant trees. But when dealing with real world data, a likely scenario is one in which not every Dependency depends on all root nodes. For example, where Z depends on Y and Y depends on A, B, C and D and 4 depends on 1 and 2 which both depend on E. In this case, there are five root nodes (nodes with no dependencies), namely A, B, C, D and E.

Taking Y, it would be possible to find root nodes A, B, C and D but because Y has no ancestral dependency on E, E would be overlooked, as would 4, 1 and 2, if trying to generate a complete structure of all the real world data present.

The DependencyForest class has been provided for this reason. It knows the context of all the Dependencies added to it.

    • setSerializingScheme

      public void setSerializingScheme (DependencyForest.SerializingScheme serializingScheme)
      Sets the direction in which to serialize this Dependency and all its dependencies. This method acts recursively on all dependencies. The serializing scheme must be set to avoid infinite recursion when serializing the Dependency. If the dependency was serialized in both direction, the recursion would never end so it must either stop when it hits the roots or when it reaches the leaves.
      Parameters:
      serializingScheme - the serializing scheme to set.

    • getRootNodes

      public Map<K,Dependency<K,V>> getRootNodes()
      Builds a ConcurrentHashMap<K,Dependency<K,V>> of all ancestor nodes of this Dependency which themselves have no dependencies or in other words, are root nodes. Remember that one Dependency leaf node or branch node can have multiple root nodes. This method acts as an initializer for the private method: private Map<K,Dependency<K,V>> getRootNode(Map<K,Dependency<K,V>> rootNodes) by passing a null value to that method so that it knows it is the first call. If this Dependency is part of a DependencyForest object, only its root nodes will be returned. To get all roots of the forest, the DependencyForest instnace methods must be used.
      Returns:
      a Map containing all root Dependency nodes.

    • treeToString

      public String treeToString()
      Mainly supplied for debugging purposes, this method generates and returns an 'ASCII art' tree representation of this Dependency tree from its point on the tree either up through the Dependency hierarchy of dependencies to the root nodes if getSerializationScheme() is DependencyForest.SerializationScheme.DEPENDENCIES or down through the Dependency hierarchy of dependants to the leaf nodes if GetSerializationScheme() is DependencyForest.SerializationScheme.DEPENDANTS.

      In practice, the method acts as the public top-level call to the recursive private method which contains the actual String building functionality. It calls the private method with recursion level 0 to start the process.

      Returns:
      a String containing the 'ASCII art' Dependency tree.
